		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message33163965">I think nil hit on one of the key features of effective deconstructions, which is that they ape genres and conventions which are culturally ubiquitous or &quot;mainstream.&quot;  Evangelion works as a deconstruction only in a context of a generation raised on super robot shows.  I (and many others) missed the wave on Evangelion; I was born in 1990 and by the time I began watching anime, the super robot shows that filled the airwaves during the 80's were gone (in large part, these shows were no longer being made <em>because</em> of Evangelion's cultural impact).  Granted, there are some themes of Evangelion that are broad enough to be recognizable in nearly any context; &quot;teenagers saving the world&quot; continues to thrive as a convention within contemporary anime.  But many genre-specific aspects of the show, like the nature of the Angels, the vulnerability of the mechs, and the impact of the conflict on Tokyo 3 were lost on me.<br />
<br />
In short, because deconstruction is built on tearing down established conventions, you can't effectively operate in a space where those conventions don't exist in the audience's head.  Without a postmodern perspective, deconstruction means nothing.<br />
<br />
Looking at deconstruction from a postmodern perspective, I think that one of the markers of an effective deconstruction is refreshing or cathartic.  Even watching Evangelion on Adult Swim as a teenager, I was able to appreciate the fact that it acknowledged and reveled in the emotional volatility of its teenage protagonists.  &quot;Maybe the task of saving the world would be best performed by those not also suffering the trial that is puberty&quot; is a thought that existed in the back of my head but never surfaced until Evangelion put that topic front and center.  Deconstruction mines and thrives on sources of cognitive dissonance in the context of other works.<br />
<br />
Incidentally, the point about effective deconstruction relying on the ubiquity of the tropes and conventions that it deconstructs makes it much more difficult for contemporary anime to emulate what Evangelion achieved in 1995.  The sheer volume of anime has increased massively since then, and there are numerous genres and subgenres that exist largely independently of one another, each with their own seperate conventions and tropes.  I think that Madoka got by largely on picking fairly generic tropes.  Like Evangelion, it picks on the fact that teenagers (teenage girls specifically in Madoka's case) are emotionally unstable and emotional instability has a host of complications and problems that come along with it.  Madoka actually took it a step further by presenting a world where teenage girls were selected precisely <em>because</em> of their emotional volatility.  &quot;Mahou shoujo&quot; as a genre is ripe for deconstruction because it's mostly just a generic set of common anime tropes (the teenage protagonist thing, and wish fulfillment and battling) mapped onto a more specific versions of these tropes (for example, specifying teenage girls).<br />
<br />
Incidentally, one of the few effective genre deconstructions in recent years that comes to mind is Devil Survivor (2008 video game in the Shin Megami Tensei series), which was an incredibly effective experience for me for many of the same reasons that Evangelion succeeded in the 90's.  Much like kids growing up in the 80's were raised on super robot anime, I was a child of the 90's raised on mons games (Pokemon, Digimon, Monster Rancher, Dragon Quest Monsters) and inherent in that genre are a lot of things that sort of get taken for granted.  Devil Survivor deconstructed the mons genre from both ends, looking at what kind of means might enable the existence of a Pokeball-like piece of technology that allows trainers to summon creatures to fight, but more importantly it examined the consequences of a world filled with monsters and monster tamers.  As it turns out, taking creatures capable of lethal force and setting them loose in an urban environment does not make for a very pretty version of Tokyo, and those without monsters are left to cower in a few select safe zones for fear of being killed by wild rampaging beasts (or extorted deliberately by domesticated monsters in the hands of the unscrupulous).<br />
<br />
To me, everything that Devil Survivor represents is absolutely delightful.  But I doubt very much that someone with no background in Pokemon or Pokemon-esque media would have the same reaction that I did.  In a vacuum, I imagine the response being something along the lines of &quot;yeah, so what?&quot;  Which basically was a big part of my early to Evangelion as a neophyte watching the dub on cartoon network.  I think that makes deconstructions inherently risky territory&mdash;you are limiting your audience right off the bat.  But they have the potential to really strike a chord when they hit the right audience.  Devil Survivor is probably my favorite game of all time, and Evangelion was the most commercially successful anime of all time.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
